# Step 5 – Staying Logged In

Imagine logging into WhatsApp every 5 minutes.

That would be annoying.

Instead,

after login,

the backend gives the app a **secure session token**.

Think of it as a temporary digital ID card.

```text
Login

↓

Backend

↓

Session Token

↓

Phone Saves Token

↓

Future Requests

↓

Token Sent Automatically
```

As long as the token is valid, the user stays logged in.

---

# Step 6 – Password Security

One of the biggest mistakes is storing passwords directly.

❌ Never store:

```text
Password

apple123
```

Instead,

store an encrypted version (called a **hash**).

Example:

```text
Password

apple123

↓

Hash

83hd82js83hd91...
```

Even if someone accesses the database, they should not be able to read users' passwords.

---

# Step 7 – Upload Security

When Alice uploads a report,

the backend should first verify:

Is Alice logged in?

If yes:

Allow upload.

If not:

Reject the request.

Never allow anonymous uploads.

---

# Step 8 – Viewing Reports

Alice requests:

```text
GET /report/123
```

Backend checks:

Does Report 123 belong to Alice?

If yes:

Return report.

If no:

Return:

```text
Access Denied
```

This prevents users from seeing someone else's data.

---

# Step 9 – Secure Communication

Imagine sending passwords over an open Wi-Fi network.

To protect data,

the app should always communicate over **HTTPS**.

HTTPS encrypts data while it travels between the phone and the server.

Think of it as sending information inside a locked envelope instead of an open postcard.

---

# Step 10 – Protecting Uploaded Reports

Blood reports are personal.

Your cloud storage should **not** allow public access.

Correct:

```text
Cloud Storage

↓

Private

↓

Only Backend Can Access
```

Wrong:

```text
Anyone with the link

↓

Can View Report
```

Always keep reports private.

---

# Step 11 – User Logout

When the user taps:

Logout

The app should:

* Remove the saved session token
* Return to the login screen

Now the user must log in again.

---

# Step 12 – If Someone Forgets Their Password

A safe reset flow looks like this:

```text
Forgot Password

↓

Enter Email

↓

Verification Link or Code

↓

Create New Password

↓

Login Again
```

Never display the user's existing password.

---

# Step 13 – Common Security Mistakes

Avoid these:

❌ Saving passwords in plain text

❌ Public cloud storage

❌ Weak passwords like "123456"

❌ Allowing users to access another user's reports

❌ Sending sensitive information over HTTP instead of HTTPS

---

# Security Checklist for Our App

Before launch, ask:

✅ Login works

✅ Passwords are securely stored

✅ HTTPS is enabled

✅ Reports are private

✅ Users only see their own reports

✅ Secure logout works

✅ Password reset works

If all are true, your app has a solid security foundation.

